---
import { Image } from "astro:assets";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import screenshot from "../assets/runebender-xilem-screenshot.png";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Runebender"
  description="Runebender is a family of experimental font editor projects: Core, Xilem, Comfy, historical Druid, and future front-end work."
>
  <main id="top">
    <section class="hero" aria-labelledby="hero-title">
      <div class="hero-copy">
        <p class="eyebrow">Core / Xilem / Comfy / Druid / Very alpha</p>
        <h1 id="hero-title">Runebender</h1>
        <p class="lede">
          A family of experimental font editor projects: shared Rust core code, a native Xilem
          editor, a ComfyUI editor path, and documentation that keeps each role distinct.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-actions" aria-label="Project links">
          <a class="button primary" href="#family">Map the family</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="/docs/index.html">Read the docs</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <figure class="screenshot-block">
        <Image
          src={screenshot}
          alt="Runebender Xilem editor screenshot showing a glyph editing workspace"
          widths={[640, 960, 1280, 1920]}
          sizes="(max-width: 1060px) 100vw, 60vw"
          loading="eager"
        />
        <figcaption>
          Runebender Xilem is the native editor path. Comfy, Core, and future editors should be
          understood as related parts of the same project family, not aliases for one app.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>
    </section>

    <section class="status-grid" aria-label="Project status">
      <div>
        <span>01</span>
        <strong>Headless core</strong>
        <p><code>runebender-core</code> is the Rust library and CLI-shaped path for non-UI font work.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <span>02</span>
        <strong>Separate editors</strong>
        <p>Xilem and Comfy are different interfaces with separate docs, status, and workflows.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <span>03</span>
        <strong>Room to grow</strong>
        <p>Druid remains project history; future front-ends can join without flattening the map.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="tool-strip" aria-label="Primary documentation paths">
      <a href="/docs/project-map.html">
        <span>MAP</span>
        <strong>Project</strong>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/core.html">
        <span>SHARED</span>
        <strong>Core</strong>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/xilem.html">
        <span>NATIVE</span>
        <strong>Xilem</strong>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/comfy.html">
        <span>GRAPH</span>
        <strong>Comfy</strong>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/druid.html">
        <span>PAST</span>
        <strong>Druid</strong>
      </a>
      <a href="/docs/support.html">
        <span>HELP</span>
        <strong>Support</strong>
      </a>
    </section>

    <section class="section family-section" id="family" aria-labelledby="family-title">
      <div class="section-kicker">Project family</div>
      <div class="section-heading">
        <h2 id="family-title">One name, several editor paths.</h2>
        <p>
          Runebender is not one finished application. Core is the headless Rust and CLI path, Xilem
          is the native editor, Comfy is the graph-hosted editor path, and Druid is the earlier
          implementation. The site should make that structure clear before asking anyone to install
          or read a manual.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="family-grid">
        <article class="family-card core-card">
          <span>Headless tool</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/core.html">Runebender Core</a></h3>
          <p>
            The Rust library and intended command-line interface for font operations that should
            work without a desktop or browser editor.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="family-card">
          <span>Native front-end</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/xilem.html">Runebender Xilem</a></h3>
          <p>
            The native desktop editor. This is where the current detailed manual, install notes,
            shortcuts, tracing workflow, and source map belong.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="family-card">
          <span>ComfyUI front-end</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/comfy.html">Runebender Comfy</a></h3>
          <p>
            The graph-hosted editor path: ComfyUI custom nodes, Vue/WASM surfaces, browser-hosted
            experiments, FONT wires, and node-based font workflows.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="family-card">
          <span>Historical front-end</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/druid.html">Runebender Druid</a></h3>
          <p>
            The earlier Druid-based Runebender implementation. It anchors the project lineage but
            should not be presented as the current front-end direction.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="family-card future-card">
          <span>Future front-ends</span>
          <h3>More hosts later</h3>
          <p>
            The family model leaves space for more editors later. New front-ends should get their
            own docs instead of inheriting Xilem-specific behavior by default.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section manual-section" id="manual" aria-labelledby="manual-title">
      <div class="section-kicker">Documentation structure</div>
      <div class="section-heading">
        <h2 id="manual-title">Shared concepts, separate manuals.</h2>
        <p>
          Common vocabulary, source formats, support, and troubleshooting stay in shared docs.
          Editor behavior belongs under the editor that actually implements it, which keeps the
          site honest while the project is still changing quickly.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="doc-index">
        <article>
          <span>Start</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/project-map.html">Understand the family</a></h3>
          <p>Core, Xilem, Comfy, Druid, and future front-ends each have a defined role.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>Native</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/xilem.html">Use Xilem</a></h3>
          <p>Build the desktop editor, open UFO sources, draw glyphs, trace images, and use shortcuts.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>Graph</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/comfy.html">Use Comfy</a></h3>
          <p>Follow the ComfyUI/Vue/WASM path for node-based font work and browser-hosted experiments.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>Headless</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/core.html">Use Core</a></h3>
          <p>Follow the Rust crate and CLI path for scripted, non-UI font operations.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>Shared</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/format.html">UFO extensions</a></h3>
          <p>Explain Runebender format conventions, including hyperbezier storage and fallbacks.</p>
        </article>
        <article>
          <span>Support</span>
          <h3><a href="/docs/support.html">Choose a channel</a></h3>
          <p>Report issues to the right repository and keep alpha behavior tied to reproducible evidence.</p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section split-section" id="reference" aria-labelledby="reference-title">
      <div>
        <div class="section-kicker">Technical surface</div>
        <h2 id="reference-title">Source and behavior.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="reference-stack">
        <table>
          <caption>Current repository map</caption>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th>Core</th>
              <td><a href="https://github.com/eliheuer/runebender-core">eliheuer/runebender-core</a></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Xilem</th>
              <td><a href="https://github.com/eliheuer/runebender-xilem">eliheuer/runebender-xilem</a></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Comfy</th>
              <td><a href="https://github.com/eliheuer/runebender-comfy">eliheuer/runebender-comfy</a></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Druid</th>
              <td><a href="https://github.com/linebender/runebender">linebender/runebender</a></td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>

        <table>
          <caption>Xilem shortcuts worth documenting first</caption>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <th>V / P / H / K</th>
              <td>Select, pen, hyperbezier pen, knife.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Space</th>
              <td>Hold for temporary preview mode.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Cmd/Ctrl + I</th>
              <td>Import background image.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <th>Cmd/Ctrl + T</th>
              <td>Trace background image into bezier paths.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section research-section" id="research" aria-labelledby="research-title">
      <div class="section-kicker">Documentation shelves</div>
      <h2 id="research-title">Find the right page quickly.</h2>
      <div class="research-grid">
        <article>
          <h3>Start</h3>
          <p>
            Project map, current facts, alpha limits, and roadmap explain what Runebender means
            before the reader chooses a front-end.
          </p>
          <a href="/docs/index.html">Open docs map</a>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>Shared</h3>
          <p>
            Glossary, format notes, support, troubleshooting, and verification stay independent
            from any one editor interface.
          </p>
          <a href="/docs/format.html">Read format notes</a>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>Xilem</h3>
          <p>
            The detailed current manual, install path, shortcut reference, tracing notes, and
            source map are native-editor docs.
          </p>
          <a href="/docs/xilem.html">Open Xilem docs</a>
        </article>
        <article>
          <h3>Comfy and Core</h3>
          <p>
            The Comfy and Core pages are intentionally lighter today, but they define clear homes
            for graph workflows, headless CLI work, and shared library behavior as those docs mature.
          </p>
          <a href="/docs/comfy.html">Open Comfy docs</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section manifesto" aria-labelledby="manifesto-title">
      <div class="section-kicker">Alpha warning</div>
      <h2 id="manifesto-title">Use copies. Verify against source.</h2>
      <p>
        Runebender is active experimental software. Keep real font sources under version control,
        confirm behavior against the current repository, and treat these docs as a map rather than
        a compatibility guarantee.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="section resource-section" id="resources" aria-labelledby="resources-title">
      <div>
        <div class="section-kicker">Links</div>
        <h2 id="resources-title">Follow the work.</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="resource-links">
        <a href="https://github.com/eliheuer/runebender-core">
          <strong>Runebender Core</strong>
          <span>Headless Rust library and CLI-shaped foundation for scripted font operations.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/eliheuer/runebender-xilem">
          <strong>Runebender Xilem</strong>
          <span>Native Rust/Xilem editor source, screenshots, shortcuts, and current desktop workflow.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/eliheuer/runebender-comfy">
          <strong>Runebender Comfy</strong>
          <span>ComfyUI custom nodes, Vue/WASM editor surface, FONT wires, and graph workflows.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/docs/current-facts.html">
          <strong>Current facts</strong>
          <span>Compact orientation page for humans, crawlers, and coding agents.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="/docs/install.html">
          <strong>Local docs</strong>
          <span>Install, manual, shortcuts, tracing, format notes, and development notes.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://github.com/linebender/runebender">
          <strong>Original Runebender</strong>
          <span>Earlier Druid implementation in the Linebender organization.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://xi.zulipchat.com/#narrow/channel/197075-runebender">
          <strong>Zulip</strong>
          <span>Development discussion in the Linebender chat.</span>
        </a>
        <a href="https://runebender.app/">
          <strong>Historical site</strong>
          <span>Older project entry point kept as project history while runebender.org becomes the current docs home.</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
